abstract={Active learning is a promising technique to reduce the images labeling effort, training time and memory usage in deep learning applications. Although active learning has proven its effectiveness in some aspects of deep neural networks, there are still some challenges. First of all, most of the current active learning researches learn knowledge from the output of the last layer while ignoring other relevant information like features; Secondly, the analysis of the informative samples is insufficient, which make the results difficult to be theoretically and intuitively explained and verified. In this paper, we propose FLONet, a Fewer Labeling cOst Active Learning neural network design for image classification. Compared to current active learning researches, FLONet is not only able to learn information about what kind of samples are rich informative, but can significantly reduce the overhead of samples labeling in the middle and late stages of training as well. Moreover, lightweight FLONet is proposed with less execution time and memory usage. From the selected informative samples, it could be observed that our method can filter out samples that are misclassified with relatively high probability. From the experiments, we tested on two public datasets and showed that this sample selection method can achieve state-of-the-art effects in terms of actively searching informative samples, and can reduce the overhead of samples labeling by the factor of 66% in FashionMNIST and 46% in Cifar10.},
