abstract={Device to device (D2D) networks coupling energy harvesting technology is a promising paradigm to enable sustainable computing for mobile devices. In energy harvesting enabled D2D networks, it is a big challenge to cooperate to execute various advanced applications by multiple energy harvesting users in a dynamically changing environment, including the available battery energy of mobile devices, the channel gain between mobile devices and the power beacon, and the number of arrival tasks. To address these challenges, we investigate multi-user cooperative task execution problem in energy harvesting enabled D2D networks with the aim to minimize the long-term cost (the weighted sum of the average latency of tasks processing, the number of dropped tasks and the battery energy penalty) for cooperative task execution. We formulate the multi-user cooperative task execution problem as a partial observable markov decision (POMDP). To solve this kind of stochastic optimization problem, we adopt a multi-agent deterministic policy gradient (MADDPG) algorithm. To demonstrate the effectiveness of the MADDPG algorithm, we firstly do experiment to analyze this algorithm ` s convergence. Then, we compare the MADDPG algorithm with Local and ECLB two baseline algorithms in terms of the total reward, the total average latency of tasks processing, the total number of dropped tasks and the total battery energy penalty. The results show that the MADDPG algorithm can converge to an optimal policy and outperforms two baseline algorithms in these performance metrics.},
